I see, thank you for clarifying that you would like a solar system representation with only HTML, CSS, and JS. Here is a simple way to create a basic solar system simulation:

1. HTML Structure: Start off with a basic HTML file with a canvas element to draw on.

2. CSS: Use CSS to style the canvas element and give it an appropriate background color.

3. JS: Define the parameters for each planet and its orbit. You can write a function to calculate the position of each planet based on its distance, inclination, and eccentricity from the sun.

4. Animations: Set up a loop that updates the position of each planet and redraws them on the canvas in real-time. You can use JavaScript's requestAnimationFrame() method to create smooth animations.

5. Draw: Use HTML Canvas methods to draw each planet as a small circle or sphere at its calculated position. You can also use HTML Canvas arc() method to draw the orbit of each planet.

Here is an example code snippet for a basic solar system representation using HTML, CSS, and JS:

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>Solar System</title>
	<style>
		canvas {
			background: black;
			display: block;
			margin: 0 auto;
		}
	</style>
</head>
<body>
	<canvas id="canvas" width="600" height="600"></canvas>
	<script>
		var ctx = document.getElementById("canvas").getContext("2d");

		var sun = {
			x: 300,
			y: 300,
			radius: 50,
			color: "yellow"
		};

		var planets = [
			{
				name: "Mercury",
				distance: 70,
				radius: 5,
				color: "gray",
				inclination: 0,
				eccentricity: 0.01,
				angle: Math.random() * Math.PI * 2
			},
			{
				name: "Venus",
				distance: 100,
				radius: 10,
				color: "orange",
				inclination: Math.PI / 4,
				eccentricity: 0.02,
				angle: Math.random() * Math.PI * 2
			},
			{
				name: "Earth",
				distance: 150,
				radius: 12,
				color: "blue",
				inclination: Math.PI / 8,
				eccentricity: 0.03,
				angle: Math.random() * Math.PI * 2
			},
			{
				name: "Mars",
				distance: 200,
				radius: 8,
				color: "red",
				inclination: Math.PI / 16,
				eccentricity: 0.04,
				angle: Math.random() * Math.PI * 2
			}
		];

		function drawPlanet(planet) {
			ctx.beginPath();
			var x = sun.x + planet.distance * Math.cos(planet.angle);
			var y = sun.y + planet.distance * Math.sin(planet.angle) * Math.sin(planet.inclination);
			ctx.arc(x, y, planet.radius, 0, 2*Math.PI);
			ctx.fillStyle = planet.color;
			ctx.fill();
			ctx.closePath();
		}

		function animate() {
			ctx.clearRect(0, 0, 600, 600);
			ctx.beginPath();
			ctx.arc(sun.x, sun.y, sun.radius, 0, 2*Math.PI);
			ctx.fillStyle = sun.color;
			ctx.fill();
			ctx.closePath();

			planets.forEach(function(planet) {
				planet.angle += 0.01;
				drawPlanet(planet);
			});

			requestAnimationFrame(animate);
		}

		animate();
	</script>
</body>
</html>
```

This is just a basic example, and you can modify the code to include more planets and more accurate orbital parameters if required.

